column12:
This question asked me to translate the English sentence 'Let's watch the sunset' into Lojban. The part of the sentence which was different was related to the English contraction 'let's'. This contraction means 'let us' so 'let us watch the sunset.' When translating the two sentences the difference was either 'mi'o' or 'mi'a'. Mi'a [pronoun] — we without you

i mi'a pu casnu do — We were discussing you. This was incorrect because it would suggest that the person that wants to watch the sunset wants to watch it with someone else. This contradicts the contraction 'let's' meaning 'let us.' Instead, the correct translation is 'mi'o. mi'o [pronoun] — you and I (the speaker and the listener). The translation is that both people (the speaker and the listener) will watch the sunset together. mi'o includes only the speaker and the listener but no one else;
mi'a includes the speaker and others but excludes the listener;
